{
  "Initiated By" : "UNITED STATES SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION",
  "Allegations" : "LITIGATION RELEASE NO. 17505, DATED MAY 7, 2002 - THE SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION ANNOUNCED THAT IT FILED A CIVIL INJUNCTIVE ACTION IN FEDERAL COURT IN MANHATTAN, CHARGING AN ATTORNEY AND FORMER STOCK BROKER WITH ILLEGAL INSIDER TRADING BY PURCHASING STOCK IN JULY 2000 WHILE IN POSSESSION OF MATERIAL, NONPUBLIC INFORMATION CONCERNING AN IMPENDING MERGER. IN MID TO LATE MAY, THE STOCK ISSUER MANAGEMENT AGREED UPON THE ESSENTIAL TERMS OF A MERGER. ON OR AROUND JUNE 7, 2000, GOLDBERG MET WITH A LONGSTANDING CLIENT TO PROVIDE LEGAL ADVICE. AT THAT MEETING, THE CLIENT COMMUNICATED TO GOLDBERG THAT: (I) ANOTHER COMPANY HAD AGREED TO ACQUIRE THE STOCK ISSUER FOR $37 PER SHARE IN CASH; (II) THE CLIENT WOULD RECEIVE A LARGE SUM OF MONEY AS A RESULT OF THE TRANSACTION; (III) GOLDBERG NEEDED TO KNOW ABOUT THE TRANSACTION BECAUSE HE WAS DOING ESTATE WORK FOR THE CLIENT; AND (IV) THE TRANSACTION WAS GOING TO BE COMPLETED. ON JULY 18, 2000 GOLDBERG PURCHASED 2,000 SHARES OF COMMON STOCK, AND CAUSED A TRUST ACCOUNT MAINTAINED FOR THE BENEFIT OF HIS MOTHER TO PURCHASE 1,000 SHARES, DESPITE HAVING BEEN WARNED BY HIS CLIENT THAT THE INFORMATION WAS CONFIDENTIAL. THE MERGER WAS ANNOUNCED ON JULY 21, 2000 AND THE STOCK ROSE OVER 40 PERCENT. BY PURCHASING THE STOCK IN ADVANCE OF THE MERGER ANNOUNCEMENT, GOLDBERG ILLEGALLY PROFITED $28,546.  ",
  "Resolution" : "Judgment Rendered",
